          "body": "The New Testament does not directly cite Leviticus 2, but the trajectory is unmistakable to any reader who has followed the grain offering's symbolic grammar to its end. The offering required the finest flour (without blemish), oil (the Spirit), frankincense (intercession and worship), and the total absence of leaven (corruption). Hebrews 10:1-10 argues that the Levitical offerings were 'a shadow of the good things to come' — they could not themselves take away sins, but they pointed to a Priest who could. Jesus, as the ultimate grain offering, is described in the New Testament as without blemish or spot (1 Peter 1:19), anointed with the Spirit beyond measure (John 3:34), offering 'a fragrant aroma' to God (Ephesians 5:2), and completely free from the leaven of sin (Hebrews 4:15; 2 Corinthians 5:21). The handful of fine flour burning on the altar in the Sinai wilderness was a grain-level portrait of the Bread of Life (John 6:35) who would one day offer Himself — most holy, soothing aroma, the salt of a new and better covenant (Hebrews 12:24)."
